[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] In cloud computing, servers may be provisioned via a web user interface or an application programming interface (API).
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] One of the unique things about cloud computing is how rapidly and easily this can be done.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Monitoring software can be used to trigger automatic provisioning when existing resources become too heavily stressed.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] In short, server provisioning configures servers based on resource requirements.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] The use of a hardware or software component (e.g. single/dual processor, RAM, HDD, RAID Controller, a number of LAN cards, applications, OS, etc.) depends on the functionality of the server, such as ISP, virtualization, NOS, or voice processing.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Server redundancy depends on the availability of servers in the organization.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Critical applications have less downtime when using cluster servers, RAID, or a mirroring system.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Service used by most larger-scale centers in part to avoid this.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Additional **resource provisioning** may be done per service.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] There are several software on the market for server provisioning such as Cobbler or HP Intelligent Provisioning.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] User provisioning refers to the creation, maintenance and deactivation of user objects and user attributes, as they exist in one or more systems, directories or applications, in response to automated or interactive business processes.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] User provisioning software may include one or more of the following processes: change propagation, self-service workflow, consolidated user administration, delegated user administration, and federated change control.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] User objects may represent employees, contractors, vendors, partners, customers or other recipients of a service.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Services may include electronic mail, inclusion in a published user directory, access to a database, access to a network or mainframe, etc.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] User provisioning is a type of identity management software, particularly useful within organizations, where users may be represented by multiple objects on multiple systems and multiple instances.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] On-demand self-service is described by the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) as an essential characteristic of cloud computing.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] The self-service nature of cloud computing lets end users obtain and remove cloud services―including applications, the infrastructure supporting the applications, and configuration― themselves without requiring the assistance of an IT staff member.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] The automatic self-servicing may target different application goals and constraints (e.g. deadlines and cost), as well as handling different application architectures (e.g., bags-of-tasks and workflows).
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Cloud users can obtain cloud services through a cloud service catalog or a self-service portal.
