[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] This refers to delivering mobile content, such as mobile internet to a mobile phone, agnostic of the features of said device.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] These may include operating system type and versions, Java version, browser version, screen form factors, audio capabilities, language settings and many other characteristics.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] As of April 2006, an estimated 5,000 permutations were relevant.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Mobile content provisioning facilitates a common user experience, though delivered on widely different handsets.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] Provisioning devices involves delivering configuration data and policy settings to the mobile devices from a central point – Mobile device management system tools.
[src:kubeadm/provisioning-technology] When getting a customer online, the client system must be configured.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] Kubeadm is a tool built to provide `kubeadm init` and `kubeadm join` as best-practice "fast paths" for creating Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] kubeadm performs the actions necessary to get a minimum viable cluster up and running.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] By design, it cares only about bootstrapping, not about provisioning machines.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] Likewise, installing various nice-to-have addons, like the Kubernetes Dashboard, monitoring solutions, and cloud-specific addons, is not in scope.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] Instead, we expect higher-level and more tailored tooling to be built on top of kubeadm, and ideally, using kubeadm as the basis of all deployments will make it easier to create conformant clusters.
[src:kubeadm/setup-tools-kubeadm] To install kubeadm, see the installation guide.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Set up Kubernetes tools on your computer.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] The Kubernetes command-line tool, kubectl, allows you to run commands against Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] You can use kubectl to deploy applications, inspect and manage cluster resources, and view logs.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] For more information including a complete list of kubectl operations, see the `kubectl` reference documentation.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] kubectl is installable on a variety of Linux platforms, macOS and Windows.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Find your preferred operating system below.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] `kind` lets you run Kubernetes on your local computer.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] This tool requires that you have either Docker or Podman installed.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] The kind Quick Start page shows you what you need to do to get up and running with kind.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Like `kind`, `minikube` is a tool that lets you run Kubernetes locally.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] `minikube` runs an all-in-one or a multi-node local Kubernetes cluster on your personal computer (including Windows, macOS and Linux PCs) so that you can try out Kubernetes, or for daily development work.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] You can follow the official Get Started! guide if your focus is on getting the tool installed.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Once you have `minikube` working, you can use it to run a sample application.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] You can use the kubeadm tool to create and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] It performs the actions necessary to get a minimum viable, secure cluster up and running in a user friendly way.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Installing kubeadm shows you how to install kubeadm.
[src:kubeadm/tasks-tools] Once installed, you can use it to create a cluster.
